{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_bradbury_ver01/data/sn92066979/00513687527/1910080801/0881.xml":{"full_text":"THE LARAMIE REPUBLICAN\nVOL. XX. NO. 3OC.\nPORTUGAL\nMAY JOIN\nBELIEVED TO BE ON POINT OF\nBREAKING WITH VATICAN OV-\nER SUPPRESSION OF A\nNEWSPAPER.\nRoman Catholic Archbishop of Braga\nOrders Suspension of Franciscan\nPublication Without Submitting\nOrder to Government for Approv\nal\u2014Spanish Officials Seize Rifles\nStored on Board Gunboat.\nLisbon, Aug. 8. \u2014Portugal, like\nSpain, is almost on the verge of a\nrupture with the Vatican, due, among\nother causes, to friction over the gov\nernmental censure of the Roman Cath\nolic Archbishop of Braga for suppres\nsing a Portuguese Franciscan paper\nwithout submitting the order to the\ngovernment for its approval.\nBitter Campaign.\nSince the issue of the royal decree\nJuly 12, nullifying the action of the\narchbishop, the clerical forces, inspir\ned, it is charged, by Cardinal Merry\nDel Vai, the papel secretary of state,\nhave been conducting a bitter cam\npaign against the government.\nRIFLES SEIZED.\nSpanish Authorities Take Possession\nof Cargo of Chartered Gunboat.\nBilbao, Spain, Aug. 8. \u2014Six thousand\nrifles were seized by the authorities\ntoday, on board a tug which had been\nchartered to go to San Sebastian,\nwhere the great anti-government dem\nonstration was proposed to be held\nyesterday.\nPlanned by Carlists.\nBefore the clerical leaders abandon\ned the manifestation, the local author\nities of San Sebastian believed that\nthe Carlists were planning to take ad\nvantage of the Catholic demonstration\nto start a movement against the gov\nernment.\nCLEANING ESTABLISHMENT.\nSOLD TO DENVERITES.\nThe Enterprise Cleaning establish\nment, owned by Mr. Razer, located on\nThird street, was gold this morning\nto Messrs Rothstein Meltz of Den\nver.\nPAYNE-ALDRICH BILL\nREVENUE PRODUCER\nFIRST YEAR\u2019S INCOME GREATER\nBY SEVENTY-FIVE MILLIONS\nTHAN ANY OTHER.\nOnly the Banner Year of 1907 Exceed\ned Revenues of Year Ended Yes\nterday Treasury Department\nMakes Public Some Figures of the\nWorking of the New Tariff Act.\n0 Washington, D. C\u201e Aug. B.\u2014 O\nO The Payne-Aldrich tariff law has O\nO produced In its first year a reve- O\nO nue greater by $75,000,000 than O\nO the sum collected in any year of O\nO the country's history, except the O\nO banner year of 1907, according to O\nO treasury department figures is- O\nO sued today. O\nO In Second Year. O\nO The second year of the opera- O\nO tions of the new tariff began to- O\nO day. O\nOOOOOOOOOOOQOOOOO\nBIG SURPLUS NOTED.\nTwenty Million Dollars Shown Up In\nCustoms Receipts.\nWashington, Aug. B.\u2014While there\nw as a deficit of $58,734,955 in the or\ndinary operations of the government in\nthe fiscal year ended June 30, 1909,\nthere was a surplus of more than $20,-\n900,000 in the year ended last Satur\nday.\nIncrease Accounted For.\nLax methods no longer prevail at\nthe customs house, It is said, and to\nthe rehabilitation of the eervlce ana\nIVIEIVIBEIR OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nthe improved morals are attributed\nthe estimated increase of twelve mil\nlions in the revenues at New York\nalone.\nTHE COTTON MARKET.\nDry Sunday in Texas Had Marked Ef\nfect in Gotham.\nNew York, Aug. 8. \u2014A comparatively\ndry Sunday in the Texas cotton belt\nwas \u2018the signal today for one of the\nmost excited buying movements the\nlocal market has experienced for some\ntime. New high levels were made by\nall positions, August advancing 26\npoints and the new crop from 31 to\n62 points.\nHERE FOR VISIT\nWITH SISTER\u2019S FAMILY.\nMrs. Lillie Light of Ogden, the sis\nter of Mrs. John Mast, ami her daugh\nter, and Miss Kate Smith, are visiting\nthe family of Will Mast on SbUth Fifth\nstreet, and will spend a part of Au\ngust in this city.\nBRITISHEARL\n10 BE ON HAND\nGRAND COMMANDER OF GRAND\nPRIORI OF ENGLAND AND\nWALES WILL ATTEND\nTEMPLAR CONCLAVE.\nGreatest Gathering of Members of\nNoted Masonic Order Ever Held\nBeginning at Chicago Today, With\nEarl of Euston a Principal Guest\nof Honor\u2014Half Million People in\nChicago to Witness Parades.\nChicago, 111., Aug. 8. \u2014This Is the Be\nginning of Knight Templar week in\nChicago. One hundred thousand\nKnights are expected to arrive today\nfor the thirty-first triennial conclave.\nBritish Grand Commander.\nToday's arrivals were to include\nEngland's foremost Sir Knight, the\nEarle of Euston, grand commander of\nthe Grand Priori of England and\nWales.\nBig Parade Tomorrow.\nTomorrow will be the first of the\n\u201cbig days,\u201d beginning with the biggest\nparade ever engaged in by Knights\nTemplar.\nHalf Million Guests.\nAt headquarters the officials today\nestimated the guests in Chicago at\nhalf a million.\nFORESTRY YOUNG MAN\nWILL BE MARRIED.\nFrank Pennock of the forestry ser\nvice, located at Foxpark, left today for\nCheyenne, where he met Miss Mabel\nYoung of Augusta, 111. The young\n.people came to Laramie this afternoon\nand will be married tomorrow. Mr.\nTalyor Pennock, a prosperous ranch\nman of Saratoga, and father of the\ngroom, is here to attend the wedding.\nCLUB ROOMSRAIDED\nAND HIGH-UPS FAINT\nHUNDRED PERSONS CAUGHT AND\nLIST OF NAMES MADE BUT\nWITHHELD BY POLICE.\nSociety Women in Evening Dress Fall\nin Faint When Officers Swoop\nDown Upon Narragansett Club at\nNarragansett Pier on Sunday\u2014\nHigh in City Social Life.\nProvidence,, R. 1., Aug 8. \u2014The raid\non the club rooms of the Narragansett\nclub at Narragansett pier yesterday\nhad unexpected results. A hundred\npersons, Including twenty or more so\nciety women, were found in the club\nrooms.\nWomen Fainted.\nSeveral of the women, who were in\nevening dress, fainted. The names of\nall present were taken, but were with\nheld by the police. Persons high in\nthe social lists of Philadelphia, New\nYork and Washington are among\nthem.\nWhy not get all the news when It Is\nnews by reading The Republican?\nLARAMIE WYOMING, Al ON DAY EVENING, AUGUST 8, 1910.\nMAD OVER\nAEROPLANE\nI\nMARVELOUS SUCCESS OF FLIGHTS\nOF SIX OF EIGHT AVIATORS\nWHO HAVE COMMENC-\nED LONG RACE.\nFirst Stage of Nearly Five Hundred-\nMile Flight Finished in Excellent\nTime and Officers Believe Result\nForeshadows Definite Conquest of\nAir\u2014lnternational Boat Contest in\nPreliminary Today.\nL\nParis, Aug. 8. \u2014All Paris is aero\nplane-mad over the marvelous success\non the first lap of the 485-mile cross\ncountry race from Issyles Molineaux\nthrough Troyes, Nancy, Mesier, Char\nleville, Douai and Amiens, in which\nsix of the eight aviators successfully\ncompleted the first stage of the trip\nto Troyes.\nConquest of the Air.\nAll the officers unite in declaring\nthat the success of the flight by so\nmany machines foreshadows the defi\nnite conquest of the air.\nWoman Yatchsman in Race.\nBoston, Mass., Aug. B.\u2014Elimination\ntrials for the right to race against the\nSpanish sender boats in the interna\ntional contest next week were com\nmenced today off Marblehead. Among\nthe yachts entered in the trials is the\nWolf, of which Miss Alice Sargent of\nBrookline, is the skipper.\nSeventeen Entries.\nThe field includes seventeen boats,\nof which seven are new this year.\nThe trials will continue three days,\nand three boats will be selected to\nmeet the Spanish craft. All three\nboats that composed last year\u2019s team,\nwhich successfully defended the Taft\ncup against the German team, are en\ntered in the trials.\nYachts of Three Nations.\nLondon, Aug. 8. \u2014Yachts of three na\ntions, Great Britain, France and Ger\nmany, are competing in the great in\nternational regatta commenced today\nat Ryde. Next year the regatta will\nbe held in French waters, and in 1912\nGermany will be in charge of the\nevent.\nwill blldtFroad\nTO STEAMBOAT SPRINGS\nNEW YORK MAN RETURNS TO\nTHAT CITY FROM THIS AND\nMAKES ANNOUNCEMENT.\nSays Railroad Is Opening Up Vast Ten.\nritory That Has Large Tonnage of\nCoal, Cattle and All Kinds of Agri\ncultural Products \u2014No Sign of\nBusiness Depression Here.\nNew York, Aug. 8. \u2014Laurence Bar\nnum, who has just returned from a\ntrip with a party of Boston and Chi\ncago bankers over the Laramie, Hahns\nPeak and Pacific railway, the road\nwhich is being built southwest from\nLaramie, on the Union Pacific into the\ncoal fields of northwest Colorado, says\nthat the railroad is opening up a vast\nterritory that has a large tonnage of\nnot only coal, but cattle and all kinds\nof agricultural products which will be\nmoved over Its lines.\nAnnounced by Management.\nIt was announced by the manage\nment just before the inspection party\nbroke up that the line would be extend\ned to Steamboat Springs, the present\nterminus of the Moffat road. Mr. Bar\nnum said:\nAlmost Freight Monopoly.\n\u201cI believe that when this road gets\ninto Steamboat Springs it will get\npractically the entire freight from that\ndistrict, which comprises 200,000 acres\nof rich agricultural valley land. The\nLaramie road will have an average\ngrade of less than 1 per cent and a\nmaximum grade of only 2 per cent,\nwhich is in favor of the way of great\nest tonnage.\nTraffic Agreement Signed.\n1 \"A tweney-five-year traffic agree\nment has been signed with the Union\nPacific and It is not expected that any\nother traffic agreements will be made.\u201d\nNo Business Depression.\n\u201cSpeaking of general conditions in\nColorado and Wyoming, Mr. Barnum\nsaid:\n\"That section of the country Is so\nbusy in railroad building, develop\nments, of coal and copper mines, tim\nber and irrigation that little is said\nabout the general depression in busi\nness.'\nLEFT FOR THE COAST\nON MONTH\u2019S VISIT.\nJudge C. E. Carpenter, his sister.\nMiss Annie Carpen*\u00ae'; W. H.\n_ us Weston and\nCrandall and \u2019ls, left\nSunday mon lor Portland, Ore., to\n?e absent u the 9th of September,\ncoming home byway of San Francisco\nand Los Angeles.\nWILLTEET\nON TUESDAY\nLARAMIE COMMERCIAL CLUB\nPRESIDENT ISSUES CALL FOR\nGATHERING AT O. K.\nPlanned to Disband Commercial Club\nand Organize Laramie Chamber of\nCommerce Instead\u2014Will Adopt\nBy-Laws and Articles of Incorpor\nation and Do Other Business.\nThe regular monthly meeting of the\nLaramie Commercial club will be held\nat 8 o\u2019clock Tuesday evening, August\n9th, at the O. K. theater. At this\nmeeting it is planned to disband the\nLaramie Commercial club and organ\nize, instead, the Laramie Chamber of.\nCommerce, the latter organization to\ntake up the same line of work as is\ntaken up by similar organizations in\nother places, and the scope of the work\nto be much broader than that former\nly taken up by the Commercial club.\nIt is proposed at the above meeting\nto adopt by-laws and articles of incor\nporation for the organization and al\nso to elect a board of nine directors,\nthe governing body of the Chamber\nof Commerce. The Chamber of Com\nmerce will start on an entirely new\nbasis, and all of the business men and\nother citizens of Laramie and Albany\ncounty are earnesly requested to be\npresent so that the various business\ninterests may be represented on the\nboard of directors.\nAn Important Matter.\nIt is certainly important to all of\nus that an organization, such as the\nproposed Chamber of Commerce, be\nstarted on a live business basis and\nkept that w\u2019ay.\nNo contributions of any kind will be\nasked for at this meeting.\nA. W. AUGSPURGER, President.\nDEAFMUTES\nIN SESSION\nFIVE HUNDRED PRESENT FROM\nEUROPE, ASIA AND AMERICA\nAT COLORADO SPRINGS\nCONVENTION.\nFirst Session of National Association\nof the Deaf and Third World\u2019s\nCongress of Deaf \u2014Christian Citi\nzenship to Be Taught at Winona\nLake Conference \u2014Priests of Fort\nWayne in Annual Retreat.\nColorado Springs, Colo., Aug. 8.\nFive hundred representatives of the\ndeaf mutes of Canada, Austria, Ger\nmany, China, England and America\ngathered here today at the first ses\nsion of the National Association of the\nDeaf and the third World\u2019s Congress\nof the Deaf. An address of welcome\nwas read from Governor Shafroth.\nTeach Christian Citizenship.\nMinneapolis, Minn., Aug. 8. \u2014A\n(Continued on page 4.1\nDETAILS OF\nCONTRACT\nI\nCHOCTAW INDIAN TELLS WHAT\nINDIANS THOUGHT THEY\nWERE COMPELLED TO\nDO TO SELL LANDS.\nHe Said He Had Been Employed By\nMcMurray to Induce Indians to\nSign Contracts for Payment of\nTen Per Cent from Sale of Coal\nand Asphalt Lands, and That In\ndians Believed They Had To.\nMcAlester, Okla., Aug. B.\u2014The con\ngressional investigation committee to\nday heard how the contracts by which,\naccording to Senator Gore, three mil\nlions in attorneys\u2019 fees were to be\nmade out of the sale of Indian coal\nand asphalt lands, were made.\nIndian On Stand.\nW. T. Hollman, a Choctaw Indian,\ntestified that he had been employed\n1 by J. F. McMurray, holder of the con\ntracts, to go out among the Oklahoma\nIndians and induce them to sign the\ndocuments.\nPaid Dollar a Head.\nAt the same time, Hollman related,\nhe was paid \u201ca dollar a head\u201d for\nsecuring the contracts appointing Mc-\nMurray to act In the tax cases.\nTen Thousand Contracts.\nIn this way McMurray obtained ten\nthousand contracts to sell land. The\nterms were 10 per cent for attorneys\u2019\nfees, or three million dollars for Mc-\nMurray and his associates.\nHollman Willing to Pay.\nHollman said he himself had siyyi\ned the 10 per cent contract because he,\nin common with other Indians, had\nbecome discouraged over the govern\nment\u2019s promise to sell the land.\nWould Pay One-Fourth.\n\u201cI would give 25 per- cent to Mc-\nMurray.\" said Hollman, \u201c17\u201c he could\nhave gotten us the money quickly.\u201d\nBelief Among Indians.\n\u201cIs it actual!}- the belief,\u201d asked Con\ngressman Saunders of Virginia,\n1 \"among the Indians that they have to\npay somebody else to get what the\n1 government has said rightfully be\n-1 longs to them?\u201d\nMust Give Up Portion.\n\u201cThat has become the belief\u2014that\nthey have to give up a good portion\nof what they get in attorneys\u2019 fees,\u201d\nreplied Hollman.\nDid Not Desire Contracts.\n1 In a statement to the committee,\nand without going on the stand today,\nMcMurray declared that the contracts\ncame to him originally against his I\ndesire.\nHeld War Council.\nHe said the Indians at a \"war coun\ncil\u201d had demonstrated their impa\ntience at the government\u2019s slowness\nin selling the land and had called up\non him to take the job at 10 per cent,\nI which he did with reluctance. Mc-\nMurray will go on the stand later.\nIndian Reiterates Statement.\nD. C. McCurtain, a Choctaw Indian,\nand attorney for his tride, today re\niterated on the stand his charges that\nMcMurray had offered him a $25,000\nbribe to withdraw tribal opposition to\nthe old contracts, which were disap\nproved by President Roosevelt.\nMADE CHARGES.\ni Jake Hamon Brings Them Against\nCongressman Creager.\nMcAlester, Okla., Aug. 8. \u2014Jake L.\nHamon made sensational charges\nagainst Congressman C. E. Creager\nthis afternoon.\nIn Guise of Loans.\nHamon charged that Creager, under\nthe guise of loans, attempted to ob\ntain large sums of money from J. F.\nMcMurray after Creager had Introduc\ned a bill in congress providing for the\nt sale of the lands.\nGONE TO DENVER TO\nTAKE SPECIAL COURSE.\nJohn Hunton of the school of music\nof the University of Wyoming has\ngone to Denver to take n special\ncourse in music In the studio of one\nof the masters located there. He will\nL return In time for the opening of the\nfall term of the school of music.\nEIGHT PAGES\nCOPPER ON HAND.\nIncrease of Two and One-Quarter Mil- t\nlion Pounds During August.\nNew York, Aug. 8. \u2014Copper stocks\non hand in the United States August\nfirst were 170,640,678 pounds, an in\ncrease of 2,254,661 pounds compared\nwith July first, according to the\nmonthly report of the Copper Produc\ners\u2019 association.\nI\nHIS LAST CONTRACT\nAS CITY WORKMAN.\nA. J. Wymore, the plasterer, Is today\ncompleting his last contract as a city\nworkman, laying a cement sidewalk\nalong both the front and side of the\nSprague property at Fourth and Fre\nmont street, occupied by Mr. and\nMrs. John Davis. He will then retire\nto his farm and devote himself to\nbucolic pursuits. Mr. Wymore has\njust completed his hay harvest, having\nforty tons more than he can feed, and\nhas alredy been offered a good price\nfor it.\nTHROWNFROH\nAUTOMOBILE\nFORMER GOVERNOR OF MISSOURI\nSUSTAINED SPRAINED WRIST\nAND BRUISES IN IOWA\nTHIS f\u2019|O: NING.\nChauffeur Loses Control of Machine\nand It Smashes Into Telegraph\nPole, Occupants Being Hurled Vi\nolently to Ground\u2014President Au\nthorizes Use of Troops in Fighting\nFire in National Forests.\nMuscatine, la., Aug. B.\u2014Former Gov\nernor Folk of Missouri had a narrow\nescape from death in an automobile\nsmash-up near Muscatine yesterday.\nHurled from Automobile.\nMr. Folk and three companions were\nhurled from the machine when the\nchauffeur lost control and smashed in\nto a telegraph pole.\nHad Sprained Wrist.\nThe former governor sustained a\nnumber of severe bruises and his right\nwrist was sprained.\nWILL FIGHT FIRE.\nPresident Taft Authorizes Use of Sol\ndiers to Protect the Forests.\nWashington, Aug. B.\u2014President Taft\nhas authorized the use of troops to\nfight the forest fires in Montana, Ida\nho. Washington, Oregon and Califor\nnia.\nforceHhaFk up\nON VICE PRESIDENT\nSENATOR GORE ISSUES STATE\nMENT DISCLAIMING USE OF\nSHERMAN\u2019S NAME.\nSaid He Never Intimated That Sher\nman Was Interested in McMurray\nContracts, But Felt Himself Under\nObligationsto Repeat What Hamon\nTold Him\u2014Warning to Democrats\nMuskogee, Olka., Aug. B.\u2014Senator\nGore has issued the following state\nment relative to Vice President Sher\nman:\nName Not Mentioned.\n\u201cI have never, either in the senate\nor before the investigating conjmittee,\nmade any charge whatever against Mr\nSherman. 1 never said he was inter\nested in the McMurray contracts, di\nrectly or indirectly. The vice presi\ndent's name was mentioned to me by\nHamon as the man higher up who was\nInterested in the contracts.\nTo Tell All He Knew.\n\u201cWhen I testified before the com\nmittee I was under obligation to re\nlate all that Hamon had said, and\nwhen It came to mentioning what\nHamon had said to me about Mr.\ni Sherman, I named the vice president\nII with extreme reluctance. I had no\ni 1 alternative but to tell the truth.\nOwes Statement to Vice President.\ni \"I think I owe it to Mr. Sherman\n(Continued on page 5.)","height":"22808","width":"16532"}}
